<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 05-12-20 - New Fan Design for 7600 Models with Cummins ISM Engine Used in Certain Vocations</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi051220" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>05-12-20</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>June, 2005</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>ENGINE</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>New Fan Design for 7600 Models with Cummins ISM Engine Used in Certain Vocations</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <distribution dealer="yes" fleet="yes" bodybuilder="no" isis_cd="yes"/>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>7600
                    <daterange>
                        <startdate>10/01/2002</startdate>
                        <enddate>12/17/2004</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>7600 Models, built between October 1, 2002 through December 17, 2004, with Cummins ISM engines
                    that are used in vocational applications, such as concrete mixer, dump truck, and gravel hauler,
                    have had fan blade breakage complaints.
                </para>
                <para>The fan blade does not come in contact with the shroud but comes close enough to cause an
                    obstruction of air flow that can lead to fan blade breakage.
                </para>
                <para>As a result, a new design is available for these vocational applications.</para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
        <partsinfo>
            <table id="t0512201">
                <tgroup cols="3" align="center">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.10*"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="1.13*"/>
                    <colspec colname="col3" colwidth="0.77*"/>
                    <thead>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Part Number</emph>
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Description</emph>
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Quantity</emph>
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>2589404C1</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>32 Inch Fan Blade</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>1</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
        </partsinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="2">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, personal injury, or death, park the vehicle on a flat level surface,
                        set the parking brake, chock the wheels, and turn the engine off.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury, allow the engine to cool sufficiently before performing this
                        procedure.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is important to note which direction the fan blades are facing on the vehicle (Figure 1)
                        before removing the fan to use as a guide for installing the new fan (Figure 2).
                    </para>
                    <para>The new design fan is offset 1/2 inch toward the engine.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the fan.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the new fan (Figure 2) with the fan blades facing the same direction as the old
                    fan.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten the fan mounting bolts to 24 to 28 Lbf-ft (33 to 38 Nm).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0512201" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G0512201.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
